knowledge_graph.title: Endive
knowledge_graph.description: Endive is a leaf vegetable belonging to the genus Cichorium, which includes several similar bitter-leafed vegetables. Species include Cichorium endivia, Cichorium pumilum, and Cichorium intybus. Chicory includes types such as radicchio, puntarelle, and Belgian endive.

related_questions.question: What does endive taste like?
related_questions.snippet: What Is the Flavor of Endive? Endives can be enjoyed both raw or cooked. When raw, endives are crisp and bitter, making them a great addition to salads. When cooked, endive's sharp flavor softens into a mellow, nutty sweetness.

related_questions.question: Is endive eaten raw or cooked?
related_questions.snippet: Belgian endive can be eaten raw or cooked and pack a tremendous amount of nutrition into very few calories – about 1 per leaf, in fact. It is high in fiber and one head delivers more than half the potassium of a whole banana as well as calcium, iron, folate and other minerals, and vitamins B, C and K.

buttons.snippet: What can you swap in for it, if need be? Chicory of endives are your best bet, but if those aren't easily accessible—they're not always! —spinach and arugula are good bitter substitutes. Truly any dark leafy green'll do.

buttons.subtitle: What Do Endives Taste Like
buttons.title: A Dive into Belgian Endive | Cook's Country - America's Test Kitchen
buttons.snippet: What Does Belgian Endive Taste Like? Belgian endive is often described as pleasantly bitter (more bitter than lettuce) and mildly nutty. The texture of Belgian endive is tender, velvety, watery or juicy, luxurious, and somewhat crisp, with a soft crunch and slight creaminess.
